{"commentv2": 1, "number": 34, "id": 1438147, "nreplies": 0, "sticky": 0, "user": "ZelosRaine", "body": "While the strategies posted here are good, I haven't seen much about the specifics of kiting for each class or about possible synergies. While I can't speak for every raid situation, I can say that, having just learned tonight how to kite these adds on my Frost DK (our Frost Mage wasn't available), there are some tips and tricks aimed at 10 mans that can't afford a third tank.\n\nObviously reading a strat isn't as a good as watching a video, but I don't have one of those for this fight. :(\n\nWhat I can say is that, if a Frost DK or any other class with similar ranged slows (mage, hunter, etc) is having trouble, here is what helped me.\n\n1) Remember, above all else, they (seem) to stack their haste and attack power buff by HITTING YOU. I know wowhead says they get a buff over time, but that is not what I saw. The first phase seems to be them hitting you. Therefore, it is imperative that you not let them hit you. Great ways to actually do this are to remember to refresh chillbains early on those mobs you picked up early as it will have worn off by the time the 5th and 6th add are up and getting ANY raid member with a stun (warrior, pally, etc) to stun them. Remember, speed debuff doesn't work if they hit you; they have to be STUNNED for you to get away.\n\n2) You cannot, unless you are uber pro, kite them by yourself. Our [url=http://www.wowhead.com/spell=49203]Hungering Cold[/url] is on too long a cooldown. Having stuns from pallys and warriors helps alot. You should save your own [url=http://www.wowhead.com/spell=49203]Hungering Cold[/url] and (hope that you have one) your mage's [url=http://www.wowhead.com/spell=82691]Ring of Frost[/url] for the final 30% of their energy.\n\nBasically, you do the following:\nDrop down, dps Ony for a few secs.\nSwitch to Blood Pres.\n[s]Howling Blast[/s] [i]Chains of Ice[/i] mobs as they come up.\n[s]If a mob is too close to you in comparison to the others, Chains of Ice it.[/s] as the mobs start to group up and their Chillbains from the Chains wear off, Howling Blast them.\nTry to run in a circle to gather the mobs behind you and then use any speed boost/leap of faith you have (I am a Worgen so, \"tee hee\") to get out in front of the pack in the direction you are supposed to drop them. If you don't have a speed boost or even if you do, this a perfect time for a Pally etc to stun them.\nOnce you are where you need to drop them, pop your Ice Bound Fortitude, run through the pack, and hit your Hungering Cold as soon as you are sure you will get them all (this needs to happen as soon as they touch you as you will die VERY fast if you try to tank them).\nWatch the timer and have your mage (cross fingers for a mage) drop their Ring of Frost with 3 seconds left, meaning that they get insta frozen again as they break out. \nOnce that wears off, simply tank the one or two who are still alive, making sure they drop right on top of the others (your phase three add tank will thank you).\nIf you don't have a mage, just stun them as soon as they break it/kite them in a tight circle and have healers use a cooldown. A few should die as your Hungering Cold breaks with more to follow. \n\nBest of luck!\n\nEdit: Not a PvP, so I never realized until I came back to kill him the next week that Chains of Ice does not have a cooldown. :P", "date": "2011-06-09T23:31:53-05:00", "rating": 4, "indent": 0, "roles": 0, "deleted": 0, "outofdate": 0, "userRating": 0, "replies": [], "dataTree": 1, "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "lastEdit": ["2011-06-27T12:46:37-05:00", 3, "ZelosRaine"]}
{"commentv2": 1, "number": 35, "id": 1439669, "nreplies": 0, "sticky": 0, "user": "Manbewbs", "body": "This comment is meant to help people doing it on 10 man hard mode, especially add tanks, and is from a warrior off tank point of view.\n\nGot this down tonight with 2 days of wiping, although we had a lot of wipes it was fun for everyone and I strongly suggest doing this hard mode before omnotron defense system if your healers and tanks are capable. It is a lot less awareness based and more of an execution fight - but one mistake can become a wipe and it is very unforgiving.\n\nOur comp was a paladin main tank, warrior off tank.\nDPS were MM hunter, Assas rogue, Feral druid, Arcane mage, and Shadow priest. \nHealers were Holy paladin, Discipline priest, and Resto shaman, all with four piece.\n\nDominion was handled with AoE snares, such as frost trap, earthbind totem, and most importantly, crippling poision as crippling is a 70% snare and makes the entire difference.\n\nFirst phase was pretty simple, I vigilance our paladin healer with righteous fury, and pick up Onyxia, bringing her to the right side of the pit, positioning does not matter as long as both dragons are separated for their buff. Pick up each Bone Construct as the Onyxia tank, letting them hit the paladin a couple of times at the beginning is fine. I suggest not spreading rend. Each time Onyxia does her flame breath, Stun the Bone Constructs on each breath, glyphed it should be up each time. Everything else stays the same with Electrocutes from Onyxia's side hitting extremely hard.\nAt around 2 million HP, we AoE CC'd the constructs, in our case a Ring of Frost from our mage. Note that if your mage gets Dominioned and you step into the ring, you will get frozen and Onyxia will deselect you, often causing a wipe.\nAll the adds die about 5 seconds after Onyxia dying, so there are no worries about them during the second phase.\nWe did not push a crackle or touch Nefarian during phase 1.\n\nPhase 2 is also pretty simple, we split our raid with 4-3-3, with a back up healer on each platform. In our case, the shadow priest, feral druid, and prot paladin were on different platforms. Each platform should have a dedicated back up interrupter. [url=http://www.wowhead.com/item=68713]Mirror of Broken Images[/url] was absolutely amazing from this point. We used them for half our raid.\nWhen you get cinders, wait for the debuff to tick to about 4 seconds. Use the trinket, start swimming into the lava, and watch it explode (Although for the first couple of attempts I'd play it safe and start heading into the lava at about 6 seconds). The resistance on the trinket makes this mechanic much more easier to heal through, and is in our opinion much more valuable than mana regen or a couple hundred DPS, as DPS and mana was not an issue on our kill. We bloodlusted during this phase to make it end as soon as possible as it's definately the most healing intensive phase. Do note that you should have a good balance of DPS on each platform, once the first Chromatic Prototype dies, the lava starts sinking and anyone on a platform will take damage after the first dominion on phase 3.", "date": "2011-06-12T02:41:44-05:00", "rating": 17, "indent": 0, "roles": 0, "deleted": 0, "outofdate": 0, "userRating": 0, "replies": [], "dataTree": 1, "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "lastEdit": ["2011-06-12T03:29:08-05:00", 1, "Manbewbs"]}
{"commentv2": 1, "number": 36, "id": 1439693, "nreplies": 0, "sticky": 0, "user": "Manbewbs", "body": "Phase 3 will be the most demanding on your healer and tanks, the main tank must always prioritize movement on your off tank, as a tail swipe or a breath will cause unnecessary damage or adds resetting. The challenge of the main tank will be to move out of fire (the first fire almost always followed him) and to have a personal CD up for every single crackle, as we had to use all the external cooldowns on the add tank.\nUsing [url=http://www.wowhead.com/item=50361]Sindragosa's Flawless Fang[/url] and the BH trinket made me not need a large CD on every other one. You can use both trinkets at the same time, providing a whopping 50%+ personal CD for every other one.\n\nI suggest saving Shield block for each crackle too (It was up for every one) as specced into [url=http://www.wowhead.com/spell=84608]shield mastery[/url] it reduced the damage even more. If you're a paladin, I strongly suggest glyphing into Divine Protection as you are most likely going to die from either nefarian's breath or a crackle.\n\nEach crackle had a raid CD, and each tanks had a CD.\n90%: raid-rallying cry, tanks-trinkets/DP\n80%: raid-trinkets, tanks-Shield Wall/GoA\n70%: raid-power word:barrier, tanks-trinket/DP\n60%: raid-trinkets, tanks-Bubble Sac/Ardent\n50%: raid-divine guardian, tanks-trinket/DP\n40%: raid-trinkets, tanks-Shield Wall/LoH\n30%: raid-spirit link totem, tanks-trinket/DP\n20%: raid-rallying cry, tanks-Pain suppresion/GoA\n10%: raid-anything left over, tanks-anything left over.\n\nSo as you see we had to coordinate CD's, and some attempts because of RNG with DPS we didn't have a CD for the raid.\n\nWhen it comes to add tanking, the first Shadowblaze should re activate all of the adds, because if you were tanking them in phase 1, they would be in a neat pile around where Onyxia died. I strongly suggest letting the adds stay in the pile of shadowblaze, having their energy bars resetting for about 10 seconds, as done incorrectly and not letting them reset for 10 seconds, they will all die at the third shadowblaze, thus making them either scattered because you were kiting them away from the third one, or them dying and instantly respawning again. Giving them a 10 second period of wallowing in the fire will make them despawn after the third shadowblaze and give your healer a lot of breathing room before the fourth one, which will ideally reactivate them all.\n\nAfter each shadowblaze, the timers between them will become faster and faster until they're at a point where a shadowblaze will come in 10 second intervals(need a confirmation, as I'm not sure on that) but they will not spawn any faster.\n\nThe key to making sure that you don't run out of room towards the end, is to move at about 2 seconds left on the shadowblaze timer, and not at the 5 second mark, when DBM usually yells at you. After kiting them away from the shadowblaze, it's usually a good idea to immediately stun them, as long as you're about 10+yards away, to reduce damage taken as shockwave or holy wrath, as long as they all don't miss, is pretty much a 100% damage reduction from melee attacks.\n\nA thing to note about stunning though, is to NOT run before the stun duration falls off IF one of your stuns miss. Reason being is that if you panic and run away because you stunned them and a shadowblaze timer is incredibly close, there is a chance that the shadowblaze will spawn underneath the add that was not stunned, so while the adds that were stunned come out of the stun and start following you, the shadowblaze that was underneath the add that wasn't stunned probably spawned while they were running towards you, and will reset their energy and it's almost guaranteed it's a wipe, depending on how many stacks of the damage increase they had when they reset.\n\nWhen positioning the adds, keep your back towards the direction you are going to kite, and the adds making a fan shape in front of you. The reason for this, is that if you keep your back towards the edge of the pit, and the adds between you and Nefarian, they will try to get to the sides of you, so that they have room for themselves (a thing all mobs do if you're used to AoE tanking) and if a shadowblaze comes and you start running, the add is likely to be trying to get to the position where they were heading towards while they were funneling around you, and then start running towards you, becoming a likely reset of their energy bar. The most frustrating time when an add resets is when one or two of them do, and 3 of them don't. It makes it much more harder to pick them up and kite shadowblazes from then on unless you purposely reset them, obviously becoming more damage that the healers need to heal on you.\n\nPaladin healers are my favorite for this (<3 josh), they have a speed increase when they pop holy radiance, and strong single tank healing and strong output cooldowns such as Avenging Wrath, Guardian of Ancient Kings, and Divine Favor when the add buff starts getting into the 10's. They also have righteous fury for when the adds die scattered. When it comes to the positioning of the healer, have them in front of you, but closer to Nefarian than you (at about 7 o' clock) and try to have him always in the front of your kite path. Healing will get tougher and tougher the longer the adds are up, so he is going to stop to hard cast a lot more the farther you get into a set of adds and will start lagging behind, sometimes ending up at about 11 o' clock. When the adds finally die, this is the healer's que to start making distance again and to regen as much as possible, as a shadow blaze is going to come soon. Use dominion to your advantage, as after dominion wears off it will give you a run speed increase.\n\nIf you end up kiting too fast and reaching fire towards the end, it may be a good idea to wait and keeping the adds in the shadowflame for 2 shadowflames before you start kiting again, but I do not know if this will work as I have not tried it (theoretically it should).\n\nAlthough this is months behind, I hope it will help you and your raid get a better understanding of the fight. Enjoy the fight! It was definitely my favorite fight this tier :)", "date": "2011-06-12T03:27:34-05:00", "rating": 17, "indent": 0, "roles": 0, "deleted": 0, "outofdate": 0, "userRating": 0, "replies": [], "dataTree": 1, "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "lastEdit": ["2011-06-14T10:39:51-05:00", 2, "Manbewbs"]}
